name: Pritish Nandy
text: We poets are not just poets. We fight for causes, we fight for the dreams of people. You can ignore poets, students, thinkers, writers at your peril. Yes, we know we are a tiny minority but we instil courage in the hearts of people. This book was inspired by the Bangladesh war. https://t.co/tWgphsltkQ

name: Pritish Nandy
text: And this is a torn, old copy of the book of Kaifi‚Äôs inspirational poems I translated during that time. Ibne Mariam spreads across three pages here, appealing to Muslims across the world to support the dream of Bangladesh. That Bangladesh exists today. A proud nation of Bengalis. https://t.co/PgqzxemGFx

name: Pritish Nandy
text: The first stanza from Kaifi Azmi‚Äôs long poem Ibne Mariam which I translated and Kaifi and I would read at every mushaira in Calcutta during the war years to drum up local support. Every time Kaifi attacked Pakistan, local Muslims would cheer. And we now question their loyalty! https://t.co/vLHo5rRvmS

name: Pritish Nandy
text: 40 years later, Sheikh Haseena prime minister of Bangladesh gives me the Liberation War Award for contributing to the war effort. I miss my friends Kaifi Azmi and film maker Sukhdev who were part of that amazing journey, reaching the first cry of Bangladesh across the world. https://t.co/JpryYqDMy4

name: Pritish Nandy
text: This too. Cover drawling by Sunil Das, capturing the anguish of the war. More poems. More insight into why the war. Since this came out last, it carried largely war poems. The book was sold on the streets of Calcutta by young Bangladeshi students to raise funds for the war effort https://t.co/nw5EMUs4Mv

name: Pritish Nandy
text: And this book appeared from Kolkata. Another bunch of compelling poems from Bangladesh translated from Bengali by me. The photograph too tells its own story. Remember, the Bangladesh war was fought on the streets by young students, poets, teachers, intellectuals. https://t.co/GHBbmtVyMc

name: Pritish Nandy
text: The book you see above was a collection of the finest poetry of the liberation war and its preceding years, translated from Bengali by me, to reach the message of the war and its purpose across the world. It was published from London by Sri Lankan poet Tambimuttu.

name: Pritish Nandy
text: Respect for @narendramodi for doing satyagraha during the Bangladesh liberation war. We young men at the time were going deep into Bangladesh, helping the muktibahini, inspiring students, tending to wounded fighters, giving them shelter in our homes in Kolkata, writing about it. https://t.co/BDg1I06le5

Fire and Ice
‚ÄîRobert Frost

Some say the world will end in fire,
Some say in ice.
From what I‚Äôve tasted of desire
I hold with those who favor fire.
But if it had to perish twice,
I think I know enough of hate
To say that for destruction ice
Is also great
And would suffice. #BOTD https://t.co/LcZUicXhEt

text: @theabhayk @bsaspoetry @holdengraber @PoetrySociety @PoetrySocietyNY @natpoetrylib @Poetry_London @PoetryFound @emergencypoet @michellebonev Abhay, for me it was always home. I often strayed. name: Pritish Nandy
text: From #ArmeniansofCalcutta by @alkanag She asks the interesting question: Were the Armenians the founders of Calcutta? Not Job Charnock as we read in our history books. https://t.co/sFaYDnEAfr

name: Pritish Nandy
text: I was lucky to have met and known them all‚Äî Mother Teresa, Jack Preger, Major Dudley John Gardiner. People who left their own country to come and help the poorest of the poor in Calcutta.

name: Pritish Nandy
text: Mother Teresa who brought so much joy and hope to Calcutta was Albanian. Jack Preger, the barefoot Welsh doctor lived his life in the slums and treated the poor free. Major Dudley John Gardiner of Salvation Army, a British army officer, fed the poor on the streets every day.

name: Pritish Nandy
text: Chanced upon this fine self-published book by @alkanag: #ArmeniansinCalcutta. A research of short texts, rare images. In school I had friends who were Armenians, Baghdadi Jews, Anglo-Indians, Chinese (escapees from Mao‚Äôs China), Bhutanese. Where has this amazing diversity gone?

text: @joybhattacharj @konkonas Mukul and I did the front page cartoon for The Telegraph for 3 years. I drew. He wrote. Then, when I came to Mumbai, I urged him to write Mindsport for me as a regular column in Illustrated Weekly and join me as editor of Science Today. I was its publisher. He quit after I did.

text: @joybhattacharj @konkonas Mukul was my neighbour in Sonali in Alipore Park Road, Calcutta. We were, he would say, ‚Äútechnically‚Äù best friends. What he meant I‚Äôve still no clue. Aparna was in Presidency in my time. We both left college unfinished. She, to make  a movie for Satyajit Ray. I, to be a poet.

Saddened to hear of the passing of Kamal Morarka. He was the only industrialist I know who entered politics without wanting anything for himself: not power, not glory.
He was a decent man motivated only by that most old fashioned of emotions: patriotism.
I will miss him

name: Pritish Nandy
text: A sad day. My friend @KamalMorarka has passed away. I shall miss his passion for good journalism, his philanthropy, his obsession for the right kind of politics. He is one industrialist who did not seek anything for himself but helped all those who came to him for help.

text: @kaushikcbasu You missed out the fire worshipping Zoroastrians. The Parsis. Homi Wadia for instance who made Hunterwali long before I was born and married Fearless Nadia. He founded Wadia Movietone and Basant Pictures. JBH Wadia too. They made a great contribution to our movies.

name: Pritish Nandy
text: RT @kaushikcbasu: Been watching old Bengali & Hindi films. What a melting pot of cultures & religions India‚Äôs film industry has been‚ÄîHindu,‚Ä¶
retweet_text: Been watching old Bengali & Hindi films. What a melting pot of cultures & religions India‚Äôs film industry has been‚ÄîHindu, Muslim, Christian, Sikh, also Judaism. Early India‚Äôs secular experiment, while far from perfect, commanded global respect. It‚Äôll be sad if this is lost.

name: Pritish Nandy
text: @stateofdelhi @Bharati09 @SanamMKhi Sadly it was the pre-Internet era and much of the decade‚Äôs work is lost. Many of my own stories and photographs too. For in those days editors didn‚Äôt only edit; they wrote too. (Funnily, one of the first things I did after quitting was open a cyber cafe to introduce the Internet)

name: Pritish Nandy
text: RT @stateofdelhi: @Bharati09 @SanamMKhi And sadly it was stopped when @PritishNandy had taken it to newer heights. I remember how reluctant‚Ä¶
retweet_text:
@Bharati09 @SanamMKhi And sadly it was stopped when @PritishNandy had taken it to newer heights. I remember how reluctantly one would let old issues go during Divali cleaning. 
Wish I had held back to those issues.

name: Pritish Nandy
text: @SanamMKhi Wish I had copies of the magazine I edited for almost a decade. It was the pre-Internet era and it‚Äôs so difficult to find those copies today. It was an era in which editors did not just edit; we wrote many of the stories too. So much of that is missing and lost to history.

text: @Iqbalsayed15 @shufta20 @Dinesh80603546 @KarnPratyaksha @Taltos2020 @QutubuddinSana @AbdurRahman_IPS @karunanundy @IPS_Association @ranjona @Aakar__Patel @hrw @suchitrav @Tanvir_Ansari @LizPuranam @TanDhesi @msaifkhalid @pzfahad @BBCHindi @yuva_journalist @shahidtantray @drsfaizanahmad @Mazharfarooqui @PrannoyRoyNDTV @IPF_ORG @IndiasMuslims @aslam_IPS @RanaAyyub @thecaravanindia @simrin_sirur @Rezhasan @shahjhan_malikk @IAMCouncil @imMAK02 @bigotry_watch @NoorRahman_IFS @suryapsingh_IAS @ZafarAafaq @raqib_naik @OfficeofUT @guardian @washingtonpost @nytimes @theindependent @HuffPost We understand your suffering. We are deeply pained by it. But till people recognise the deep injustice that underlies such despicable acts of violence, things cannot improve. I said Sabr because with patience comes wisdom. Wisdom for your tormentors and justice for your people.

name: Pritish Nandy
text: @tathagat_Budha @Iqbalsayed15 @Taltos2020 @QutubuddinSana @AbdurRahman_IPS @karunanundy @shufta20 @IPS_Association @ranjona @Aakar__Patel @hrw @suchitrav @Tanvir_Ansari @LizPuranam @TanDhesi @msaifkhalid @pzfahad @BBCHindi @yuva_journalist @shahidtantray @drsfaizanahmad @Mazharfarooqui @PrannoyRoyNDTV @IPF_ORG @IndiasMuslims @aslam_IPS @RanaAyyub @thecaravanindia @simrin_sirur @Rezhasan @shahjhan_malikk @IAMCouncil @imMAK02 @bigotry_watch @NoorRahman_IFS @suryapsingh_IAS @ZafarAafaq @raqib_naik @OfficeofUT @guardian @washingtonpost @nytimes @theindependent @HuffPost But the opposite of patience is to say go, seek revenge. Surely that is not what you want me to say. Justice is a must. And the guilty must be caught and punished. By how do you achieve that when hate is being actively encouraged by those who dominate our public lives.
